{
  "text": "Norm stability. Norm stability reflects the extent to which norm homogeneity and strength remain constant over time. Changes in friendship group membership may influence norm stability, but prior research has not directly addressed this issue. Highly fluid groups may experience norm change, thus reducing norm stability. Alternatively, norms may be resistant to changes in composition. For instance, incoming group members may be subject to the same expectations as existing members. In addition, new group members may be selected by or attracted to groups on the basis of shared values (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
